  "original_title": "\u2018\u2018\u0dc0\u0dd2\u0daf\u0dd9\u0dc3\u0dca \u0d9c\u0dad \u0dc0\u0db1\u0dca\u0db1\u0da7 \u0db4\u0dd9\u0dbb \u0db8\u0dd0\u0dbd\u0dda\u0dbb\u0dd2\u0dba\u0dcf\u0dc0\u0da7 \u0db6\u0dd9\u0dc4\u0dd9\u0dad\u0dca \u0d9c\u0db1\u0dca\u0db1\u2018\u2018",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "\"Take Malaria Medicine Before Traveling Abroad\"",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "The National Malaria Headquarters urges all Sri Lankans traveling abroad to use anti-malarial drugs and to carry a certain amount of those drugs with them.",
        "Sri Lankans traveling abroad should pay close attention to the fact that malaria has been reported in many countries including Africa, India, Thailand and Sudan, said Dr. Naveen De Soysa, senior registrar of community medicine at the headquarters.",
        "He said that when the malaria parasite enters the body, the mosquito spreads the disease.",
        "Malaria was completely eradicated from the country by 2016 and twenty seven cases have been reported this year. In 1963, 12 cases were reported and during 1965-67, although the number of cases was more than thousands, Sri Lanka was completely free of malaria, said Dr. Soysa."
      ],
